{"nodes":[{"content":"Map DirectX 9 features to DirectX 11 APIs","pos":[27,68]},{"content":"Understand how the features your Direct3D 9 game uses will translate to Direct3D 11 and the Universal Windows Platform (UWP).","pos":[82,207]},{"content":"Map DirectX 9 features to DirectX 11 APIs","pos":[264,305]},{"content":"Updated for UWP apps on Windows 10.","pos":[311,346]},{"content":"For Windows 8.x articles, see the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>archive<ept id=\"p1\">](http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/p/?linkid=619132)</ept>","pos":[347,439]},{"content":"Summary","pos":[446,453]},{"content":"Plan your DirectX port","pos":[462,484]},{"content":"Important changes from Direct3D 9 to Direct3D 11","pos":[518,566]},{"content":"Feature mapping","pos":[610,625]},{"content":"Understand how the features your Direct3D 9 game uses will translate to Direct3D 11 and the Universal Windows Platform (UWP).","pos":[628,753]},{"content":"Mapping Direct3D 9 to DirectX 11 APIs","pos":[758,795]},{"pos":[798,955],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Direct3D<ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/desktop/hh309466)</ept> is still the foundation of DirectX graphics, but the API has changed since DirectX 9:"},{"content":"Microsoft DirectX Graphics Infrastructure (DXGI) is used to set up graphics adapters.","pos":[961,1046]},{"content":"Use <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>DXGI<ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/desktop/hh404534)</ept> to select buffer formats, create swap chains, present frames, and create shared resources.","pos":[1047,1209]},{"content":"See <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>DXGI Overview<ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/desktop/bb205075)</ept>.","pos":[1210,1291]},{"content":"A Direct3D device context is used to set pipeline state and generate rendering commands.","pos":[1296,1384]},{"content":"Most of our samples use an immediate context to render directly to the device; Direct3D 11 also supports multithreaded rendering, in which case deferred contexts are used.","pos":[1385,1556]},{"content":"See <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Introduction to a Device in Direct3D 11<ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/desktop/ff476880)</ept>.","pos":[1557,1664]},{"content":"Some features have been deprecated, most notably the fixed function pipeline.","pos":[1669,1746]},{"content":"See <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Deprecated Features<ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/desktop/cc308047)</ept>.","pos":[1747,1834]},{"pos":[1836,2053],"content":"For a full list of Direct3D 11 features, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Direct3D 11 Features<ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/desktop/ff476342)</ept> and <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt>Direct3D 11 Features<ept id=\"p2\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/desktop/hh404562)</ept>."},{"content":"Moving from Direct2D 9 to Direct2D 11","pos":[2058,2095]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Direct2D (Windows)<ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/desktop/dd370990)</ept> is still an important part of DirectX graphics and Windows.","pos":[2098,2239]},{"content":"You can still use Direct2D to draw 2D games, and to draw overlays (HUDs) on top of Direct3D.","pos":[2240,2332]},{"content":"Direct2D runs on top of Direct3D; 2D games can be implemented using either API.","pos":[2334,2413]},{"content":"For example, a 2D game implemented using Direct3D can use orthographic projection, set Z-values to control the drawing order of primitives, and use pixel shaders to add special effects.","pos":[2414,2599]},{"content":"Since Direct2D is based on Direct3D it also uses DXGI and device contexts.","pos":[2601,2675]},{"content":"See <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Direct2D API Overview<ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/desktop/dd317121)</ept>.","pos":[2676,2765]},{"content":"The <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>DirectWrite<ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/desktop/dd368038)</ept> API adds support for formatted text using Direct2D.","pos":[2767,2897]},{"content":"See <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Introducing DirectWrite<ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/desktop/dd371554)</ept>.","pos":[2898,2989]},{"content":"Replace deprecated helper libraries","pos":[2994,3029]},{"content":"D3DX and DXUT are deprecated and cannot be used by UWP games.","pos":[3032,3093]},{"content":"These helper libraries provided resources for tasks such as texture loading and mesh loading.","pos":[3094,3187]},{"pos":[3193,3383],"content":"The <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Simple port from Direct3D 9 to UWP<ept id=\"p1\">](walkthrough--simple-port-from-direct3d-9-to-11-1.md)</ept> walkthrough demonstrates how to set up a window, initialize Direct3D, and do basic 3D rendering."},{"pos":[3388,3594],"content":"The <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Simple UWP game with DirectX<ept id=\"p1\">](tutorial--create-your-first-metro-style-directx-game.md)</ept> walkthrough demonstrates common game programming tasks including graphics, loading files, UI, controls, and sound."},{"pos":[3599,3749],"content":"The <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>DirectX Tool Kit<ept id=\"p1\">](http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/p/?LinkID=248929)</ept> community project offers helper classes for use with Direct3D 11 and UWP apps."},{"content":"Move shader programs from FX to HLSL","pos":[3754,3790]},{"content":"The D3DX utility library (D3DX 9, D3DX 10, and D3DX 11), including Effects, is deprecated for UWP.","pos":[3793,3891]},{"content":"All DirectX games for UWP drive the graphics pipeline using <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>HLSL<ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/desktop/bb509561)</ept> without Effects.","pos":[3892,4036]},{"content":"Visual Studio still uses FXC under the hood to compile shader objects.","pos":[4038,4108]},{"content":"UWP game shaders are compiled ahead of time.","pos":[4109,4153]},{"content":"The bytecode is loaded at runtime, then each shader resource is bound to the graphics pipeline during the appropriate rendering pass.","pos":[4154,4287]},{"content":"Shaders should be moved to their own separate .HLSL files and rendering techniques should be implemented in your C++ code.","pos":[4288,4410]},{"pos":[4412,4551],"content":"For a quick look at loading shader resources see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Simple port from Direct3D 9 to UWP<ept id=\"p1\">](walkthrough--simple-port-from-direct3d-9-to-11-1.md)</ept>."},{"content":"Direct3D 11 introduced Shader Model 5, which requires Direct3D feature level 11<ph id=\"ph1\">\\_</ph>0 (or above).","pos":[4553,4647]},{"content":"See <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>HLSL Shader Model 5 Features for Direct3D 11<ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/desktop/ff471419)</ept>.","pos":[4648,4760]},{"content":"Replace XNAMath and D3DXMath","pos":[4765,4793]},{"content":"Code using XNAMath (or D3DXMath) should be migrated to <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>DirectXMath<ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/desktop/hh437833)</ept>.","pos":[4796,4926]},{"content":"DirectXMath includes types that are portable across x86, x64, and ARM.","pos":[4927,4997]},{"content":"See <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Code Migration from the XNA Math Library<ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/desktop/ee418730)</ept>.","pos":[4998,5106]},{"content":"Note that DirectXMath float types are convenient for use with shaders.","pos":[5108,5178]},{"content":"For example <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>XMFLOAT4<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/desktop/ee419608)</ept> and <bpt id=\"p3\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p4\">**</bpt>XMFLOAT4X4<ept id=\"p4\">**</ept><ept id=\"p3\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/desktop/ee419621)</ept> conveniently align data for constant buffers.","pos":[5179,5394]},{"content":"Replace DirectSound with XAudio2 (and background audio)","pos":[5399,5454]},{"content":"DirectSound is not supported for UWP:","pos":[5457,5494]},{"pos":[5500,5609],"content":"Use <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>XAudio2<ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/desktop/hh405049)</ept> to add sound effects to your game."},{"content":"Replace DirectInput with XInput and UWP APIs","pos":[5615,5659]},{"content":"DirectInput is not supported for UWP:","pos":[5662,5699]},{"pos":[5705,5843],"content":"Use <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>CoreWindow<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/br208225)</ept> input event callbacks for mouse, keyboard, and touch input."},{"content":"Use <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>XInput<ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/desktop/ee417001)</ept> 1.4 for game controller support (and game controller headset support).","pos":[5848,5992]},{"content":"If you are using a shared code base for desktop and UWP, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>XInput Versions<ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/desktop/hh405051)</ept> for information on backwards compatibility.","pos":[5993,6176]},{"pos":[6181,6315],"content":"Register for <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>EdgeGesture<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/hh701600)</ept> events if your game needs to use the app bar."},{"content":"Use Microsoft Media Foundation instead of DirectShow","pos":[6320,6372]},{"content":"DirectShow is no longer part of the DirectX API (or the Windows API).","pos":[6375,6444]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Microsoft Media Foundation<ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/desktop/ms694197)</ept> provides video content to Direct3D using shared surfaces.","pos":[6445,6592]},{"content":"See <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Direct3D 11 Video APIs<ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/desktop/hh447677)</ept>.","pos":[6593,6683]},{"content":"Replace DirectPlay with networking code","pos":[6688,6727]},{"content":"Microsoft DirectPlay has been deprecated.","pos":[6730,67